I'm depressed that I seem to be the only student (or one of the few) struggling on the LLM. I understand only half of what is going on while other people seem to have managed to do much more reading, understand much more and have many more ideas than me in class. My dissertation topic is hopeless while everyone else seems enthusiastic‚Ä¶ More about theirs. I thought things would improve as the term progressed and I adapted more to the programme but they didn't. When I think I've finally managed something - a formative assessment - I get a 2:2 on it. I can't accept that such is my academic (in)ability when I'm already a postgrad, I've done an undergrad degree where I performed above average and better than most people around me, and I've done a professional qualification as well. And I have so many modules plus the dissertation that a one-month holiday won't be enough for me to catch up.

To the person who wrote  about male pattern baldness -- There's hope! Look into finasteride and minoxidil, you can get a perscription for both pretty easily from your GP. Finasteride works on 90+% of people, and it works really well. Although the side effects are scary, they're extremely rare and relatively overblown. Do your own research, talk to your GP, and see if its right for you. Good luck bro (P.s. you can get generic finasteride online for really cheap, compared to the brand names sold in pharmacies).

Parts of the national capital saw their internet getting suspended for days and Kashmir has been in complete lockdown for six months. Protestors have been killed by the police in Assam. Yet, I did not see this get the kind of international attention that other mobilisations on a similar scale have gotten. We are not talking about this enough and we have to, and Indians like me who have the privilege to study abroad need to bring our friends and peers from other communities into the fold. More importantly,our privilege and wealth hide the harsh realities that other Indians face which I only experienced first hand because it happened next door #caa#nrc

Why are gender identity and sexuality grouped under the same term 'LGBTQ+'. I say this as a gay man who is a supporter of the trans community. While both communities still have a long way to go in terms of equality, the LGB definitely has a lot more recognition and has received a lot more attention in recent years, whilst I feel it is‚Ä¶ More much harder to be a member of the trans community in today's society. I worry that we hail LGBT progress when we are actually only really seeing progress for the LGB community and the trans community is being left behind. But because they all come under the same banner we forget about trans issues. Also sexuality and gender identity are two completely separate issues. Yes, gay people can support the trans community (and vice versa) but we will never truly understand what it means to question your gender identity. The label LGBTQ+ feels to me like "Oh these people aren't 'normal' let's shove them all under the same label".

Actually, while it may not matter to you or your friends in 5 years time, it will still matter to the students whose ability to reach university is impeded by their earlier eduction. You may think that the debate is "stupid" because you worked hard at private school but this argument is not based off of how hard we all‚Ä¶ More worked. You have to work hard to get into top universities like UCL whether you went to private school or state school. There is no argument about that. However, the standard that state schools are held to is much lower than that which private schools are held to, meaning that students are not given the same opportunities and their educational experience does not match that which is given in private schools. I get that a lot of people are making this debate about hard work, admittedly because a lot of us are jealous of the increased opportunities available to students who go to private schools, but it is inherently about equality of opportunity.

Tbh Paramore were really snubbed at the Grammys and I'm still mad, After Laughter was a work of pure genius. Why is it that people say you can't be racist to white people? Whilst I agree white people do not suffer from structural racism (which I think to be the worst form of racism) which other races do, I still think you CAN be racist to white people. In fact, I think you can be racist to anyone. Google says the definition of racism is:‚Ä¶ More prejudice, discrimination, or antagonism directed against someone of a different race based on the belief that one's own race is superior. And I see no reason as to why white people cannot fit into that. Yes, obviously it isn't structural racism like I said, but there are people who joke about white people but then become sensitive when people make jokes about their own race. I just don't agree with the hypocrisy. Why can't we just all get along and stop stereotyping each other.
